<paragraph blockId="14.[212,1173,1309,1692]" lastBlockId="15.[144,1104,1560,1680]" lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="1614" pageId="14" pageNumber="1613">
Head similar to male but labrum (
<figureCitation box="[672,794,1348,1372]" captionStart="Figure 17" captionStartId="16.[212,279,986,1008]" captionTargetBox="[212,1172,168,954]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[212,1172,168,954]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Figure 17. Megaselia speiseri female, proboscis and palps." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4006350" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4006350/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="1613">Figure 17</figureCitation>
) about 1.5 times wider than diameter of postpedicel. Labella paler, with submarginal pale greyish bands above and only about a dozen, widely spaced, bristles reduced to small spinules below and at tips. Otherwise head similar to male. Thorax as in the male in that it has three notopleural bristles, 0–9 (mean: 5) hairs on mesopleuron and the scutellum with an anterior pair of hairs (about as strong as those in middle of scutum) and a posterior pair of bristles. Abdominal tergites brown. T3–T6 as 
<figureCitation box="[212,329,1571,1595]" captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="17.[144,211,920,942]" captionTargetBox="[144,1104,168,888]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[144,1104,168,888]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Figure 18. Megaselia speiseri female. details of abdomen, tergites 3–6." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4006352" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4006352/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="1613">Figure 18</figureCitation>
. Terminal segments as in 
<figureCitation box="[656,773,1571,1595]" captionStart="Figure 19" captionStartId="18.[212,279,735,757]" captionTargetBox="[212,1172,168,703]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[212,1172,168,703]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Figure 19. Megaselia speiseri female, terminal segments and cerci." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4006354" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4006354/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="1613">Figure 19</figureCitation>
. Venter grey, and typically with hairs below segments 3–6, but sometimes none on 3, Sternite 7 and lobes at rear of sternum 8 as 
<figureCitation box="[407,523,1635,1659]" captionStart="Figure 20" captionStartId="18.[209,276,1432,1454]" captionTargetBox="[209,1169,811,1401]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[209,1169,811,1401]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Figure 20. Megaselia speiseri female, sternite 7." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4006356" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4006356/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="1613">Figure 20</figureCitation>
. Cerci brown and at most 1.5 times as long as broad. Furca not evident. Dufour’ s crop mechanism as in 
<figureCitation box="[850,968,1667,1691]" captionStart="Figure 21" captionStartId="19.[144,211,705,727]" captionTargetBox="[144,1104,168,674]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[144,1104,168,674]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Figure 21. Megaselia speiseri female, Dufour’s crop mechanism (anterior end to right)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4006358" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4006358/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="1613">Figure 21</figureCitation>
. Legs similar to male. Wing as in male except 
<quantity box="[514,654,1560,1584]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.45" metricValueMax="1.6" metricValueMin="1.3" pageId="15" pageNumber="1614" unit="mm" value="1.45" valueMax="1.6" valueMin="1.3">1.3–1.6 mm</quantity>
long. Costal index 0.44–0.46. Costal ratios 2.5–4.2:1.1–1.5:1. Costal cilia 0.06–00.09 mm long. With two to three axillary bristles, the outermost being longer than the costal cilia. Otherwise it and haltere as male.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
