<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="1615" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="16.[212,1172,1071,1262]" box="[212,319,1071,1095]" pageId="16" pageNumber="1615">
<heading box="[212,319,1071,1095]" fontSize="10" level="3" pageId="16" pageNumber="1615" reason="5">
<emphasis box="[212,319,1071,1095]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="1615">Comment</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[212,1172,1071,1262]" pageId="16" pageNumber="1615">
Variation in the number of the relatively few hairs on the mesopleuron includes a single female with a bare mesopleuron. A male with such a bare mesopleuron will fail to key out in the key to the males recorded from the British Isles (
<bibRefCitation author="Disney RHL" box="[980,1122,1174,1198]" pageId="16" pageNumber="1615" pagination="1 - 155" refId="ref8043" refString="Disney RHL. 1989. Scuttle Flies - Diptera Phoridae Genus Megaselia. Handbk Ident Br Insects. 10: 1 - 155." type="journal article" year="1989">Disney 1989</bibRefCitation>
), or else its hypoppygium (
<emphasis box="[468,551,1206,1230]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="1615">loc. cit.</emphasis>
fig. 318) obviously differs from those it may run to in the key, especially in having more than nine hairs on each cercus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
